Indonesia Equity Movers: Medco, International Nickel, Timah

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-08-05T09:16:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-05/indonesia-stocks-medco-energi-international-nickel-timah.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  tumbled 200.44 points, or 4.9
percent, to 3,921.64, the sharpest drop since Nov. 13, 2008. The
measure fell 5.1 percent this week, the most since the week
ended Jan. 21.  Energy companies: PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),
Indonesia’s largest listed oil company, slumped 5.1 percent to
2,350 rupiah, the biggest drop since Nov. 3. PT Energi Mega
Persada (ENRG IJ), the second-largest, plunged 13 percent to 210
rupiah, the steepest decline since Aug. 19, 2010.  Crude futures sank 5.8 percent to $86.63 a barrel in  New
York  yesterday, erasing all of its gains for 2011. Oil extended
losses today, dropping as much as 4.3 percent to $82.87 in
after-hours trading.  PT International Nickel  Indonesia  (INCO IJ), the nation’s
biggest producer of the metal, declined 6.1 percent to 3,825
rupiah, falling for a fourth day. President Director Tony Wenas
plans to resign in September, Kontan reported, citing a person
it didn’t identify. Wenas, who was appointed to the job in March
last year, declined to comment, the report said. Four calls to
the company’s office in Jakarta weren’t answered.  PT Pabrik Kertas Tjiwi Kimia (TKIM IJ), an Indonesian paper
producer, declined 8.2 percent to 2,250 rupiah, the biggest drop
since May 25, 2010. The company reported today first-half net
income fell 45 percent from a year earlier to $40.85 million.  PT Timah (TINS IJ), the nation’s largest tin producer, sank
11 percent to 2,100 rupiah, the biggest decline since Oct. 8,
2008. Tin fell 3 percent to $25,505 a metric ton in  London 
yesterday, bringing its three-day loss to 9.2 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
